{
  "texts": [
    "It is therefore not",
    "10.3389/fpsyg.2024.1368265 Frontiers in Psychology 03 frontiersin.org",
    "surprising that police officers who live through distinct experiences then form understandings of the world that are distinct from those that do not.",
    "This gradual collection of distinct experiences then leads to a distinct development of cognitive processing, built upon experiences that non-officers do not share; to summarize, it theoretically sets officers cognitively apart from other professions.",
    "This was explored by Smith et al. (2006) in their investigation of whether prior experience influenced their application of suspicion, with gender providing some significant relationships with suspicion formation."
  ]
}